      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/no-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Primary hemolysis validation — comparator link absent",
      "description": "CFD-predicted relative hemolysis index (RHI) values were computed for all five flow-speed operating points defined in the COU. Predicted RHI values ranged from 0.61 to 0.94 across the operating envelope, with the worst-case point at 3 L/min / 3500 RPM yielding RHI = 0.94. The assessment narrative references the Herbertson et al. (2015) in-vitro hemolysis dataset as the intended experimental comparator; however, no formal comparedAgainst linkage to that dataset has been established in this record. Agreement between CFD predictions and the referenced experimental values is described qualitatively as 'within acceptable scatter' in the project technical report (PTR-CPB-2024-07), but no quantitative metric or formal comparator object is bound to this result. The absence of the comparedAgainst link means the inference from simulation output to RH < 1 acceptance cannot be formally traced through the evidence graph.",
      "quantitativeMetric": "RHI_worst_case = 0.94 (CFD); acceptance criterion RH < 1.0",
      "assessmentDate": "2026-03-15T00:00:00Z"
    },
    {
      "id": "https://uofa.net/synth/validation/mismatched-comparator",
      "type": "ValidationResult",
      "name": "Secondary hemolysis validation — steady-state comparator mismatched to pulsatile COU",
      "description": "A second validation activity compared CFD predictions against the FDA benchmark steady-state hemolysis dataset (NCBI BioProject PRJNA612105), which was acquired under constant-flow conditions at fixed impeller speeds with no pulsatile waveform. The COU explicitly requires evaluation under cardiopulmonary bypass conditions, where arterial pulsatility is partially preserved and the pump inlet experiences flow waveforms with peak-to-trough ratios of approximately 1.8:1 at physiological heart rates (60–80 bpm). The steady-state comparator dataset does not capture the transient shear stress histories that drive pulsatile hemolysis augmentation; consequently, the experimental conditions of the comparator are structurally inconsistent with the declared COU. Despite this mismatch, the validation activity was scored as satisfactory and used to support the Output Comparison factor assessment. This constitutes an undercutting defeater: the inference method (steady-state experimental comparison) does not support the claim being made (CFD adequacy under pulsatile CPB conditions).",
